1
00:00:00,080 --> 00:00:05,280
Let me tell you a secret: price action and 
candlestick psychology is what separates  

2
00:00:05,280 --> 00:00:10,520
the true market masters from the rest. 
 
You see, every candlestick on your chart is  

3
00:00:10,520 --> 00:00:16,680
a visual representation of the decisions made 
by thousands of traders, each acting on their  

4
00:00:16,680 --> 00:00:22,800
own beliefs, fears, and expectations.
 
Well, candlestick psychology is about  

5
00:00:22,800 --> 00:00:26,680
understanding that the market is 
not just a series of random candles,  

6
00:00:26,680 --> 00:00:30,960
but a reflection of human behavior.
So let’s talk about it. This is  

7
00:00:30,960 --> 00:00:37,280
how I personally read each candle! 
 
A long candlestick, also called a trend candle,  

8
00:00:37,280 --> 00:00:42,560
whether bullish or bearish, represents a 
significant imbalance between buyers and  

9
00:00:42,560 --> 00:00:46,720
sellers during that time period.
The length of the candle body  

10
00:00:46,720 --> 00:00:52,320
reflects the intensity of this imbalance.
 
A long bullish candlestick forms when the  

11
00:00:52,320 --> 00:00:56,440
closing price is significantly 
higher than the opening price. 

12
00:00:56,440 --> 00:01:02,040
In terms of supply and demand, this indicates 
that buyers were in complete control during  

13
00:01:02,040 --> 00:01:08,200
this period. They aggressively bid up 
prices, absorbing any available supply. 
  

14
00:01:08,200 --> 00:01:14,000
The lack of upper wick suggests that buyers 
remained in control until the very end of the  

15
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:20,360
candle, with the closing price near the high.
This type of candle often signals strong  

16
00:01:20,360 --> 00:01:23,320
bullish sentiment.
Buyers are confident  

17
00:01:23,320 --> 00:01:28,440
and willing to push prices higher.
 
It can potentially indicate the start of a new  

18
00:01:28,440 --> 00:01:34,840
uptrend or the continuation of an existing one.
The psychology here is one of optimism  

19
00:01:34,840 --> 00:01:39,600
and aggression from the buyers.
 
On the flip side, a long bearish  

20
00:01:39,600 --> 00:01:45,360
candlestick forms when the closing price is 
significantly lower than the opening price. 

21
00:01:45,360 --> 00:01:51,040
This indicates that sellers dominated the 
session, aggressively pushing prices lower. 
  

22
00:01:51,040 --> 00:01:56,720
The lack of lower wick suggests that 
sellers remained in control until the close,  

23
00:01:56,720 --> 00:02:01,640
with the price ending near the low.
This type of candle signals strong  

24
00:02:01,640 --> 00:02:08,400
bearish sentiment. Sellers are confident and in 
control, potentially indicating the start of a new  

25
00:02:08,400 --> 00:02:15,040
downtrend or the continuation of an existing one.
The psychology here is one of pessimism and  

26
00:02:15,040 --> 00:02:19,120
aggression from the sellers.
 
 
 
A short candlestick, whether  

27
00:02:19,120 --> 00:02:25,640
bullish or bearish, represents a period of 
relative balance between buyers and sellers. 

28
00:02:25,640 --> 00:02:31,760
The small size of the candle body indicates 
that neither side was able to gain a significant  

29
00:02:31,760 --> 00:02:36,600
advantage during that time frame.
 
 
From a supply and demand perspective,  

30
00:02:36,600 --> 00:02:43,440
a short candlestick suggests that the forces of 
buying and selling were largely in equilibrium. 

31
00:02:43,440 --> 00:02:49,520
This type of candle often indicates a period 
of indecision or consolidation in the market. 
 

32
00:02:49,520 --> 00:02:56,280
Neither buyers nor sellers have a clear advantage, 
leading to a relatively narrow trading range. 

33
00:02:56,280 --> 00:03:02,240
The psychology here is one of uncertainty 
and caution from both sides of the market.
  

34
00:03:02,240 --> 00:03:05,240
When a series of short candlesticks appear,  

35
00:03:05,240 --> 00:03:12,080
it may show declining momentum in the current 
trend or be a symptom of sideways movement.
 
  

36
00:03:12,080 --> 00:03:17,880
A doji candle forms when the opening 
and closing prices are virtually equal. 

37
00:03:17,880 --> 00:03:22,320
This means that despite any price 
fluctuations during the period,  

38
00:03:22,320 --> 00:03:28,680
buyers and sellers were ultimately in balance, 
neither side being able to gain the upper hand.
  

39
00:03:28,680 --> 00:03:34,400
From a supply and demand perspective, a doji 
represents a moment of indecision, a pause  

40
00:03:34,400 --> 00:03:41,160
in the ongoing war between buyers and sellers.
 
As the candle opens, buyers attempt to bid prices  

41
00:03:41,160 --> 00:03:47,320
higher, while sellers attempt to drive prices 
lower. Over the course of the period, neither  

42
00:03:47,320 --> 00:03:53,800
side is able to maintain a significant advantage.
Every advance by the buyers is met with equal  

43
00:03:53,800 --> 00:03:59,720
selling pressure, and every decline instigated 
by the sellers is met with equal buying support. 

44
00:04:00,920 --> 00:04:05,760
This back-and-forth results in the price 
oscillating around the open, ultimately  

45
00:04:05,760 --> 00:04:11,200
closing at or very near the same level. 
 
From a psychological standpoint,  

46
00:04:11,200 --> 00:04:15,920
a doji suggests that the market is 
at a crossroads. The previous trend,  

47
00:04:15,920 --> 00:04:22,240
whether bullish or bearish, has lost momentum.
Market participants are reassessing their  

48
00:04:22,240 --> 00:04:29,720
positions, reevaluating their convictions in light 
of new information or shifting market dynamics. 

49
00:04:30,240 --> 00:04:36,440
This moment of collective hesitation can be 
a precursor to significant market moves. 
  

50
00:04:36,440 --> 00:04:42,400
Candlesticks with long upper and lower wicks 
on both sides of the real body represent a  

51
00:04:42,400 --> 00:04:49,640
period of significant volatility and indecision.
 
As the candle opens, buyers push prices higher,  

52
00:04:49,640 --> 00:04:54,320
as indicated by the long upper wick. 
This shows that there was significant  

53
00:04:54,320 --> 00:04:59,880
buying pressure during this period.
However, at the higher prices, sellers  

54
00:04:59,880 --> 00:05:06,840
stepped in aggressively, driving prices back down.
The long lower wick shows that sellers were able  

55
00:05:06,840 --> 00:05:12,840
to push prices significantly lower.
But here they meet strong opposition.  

56
00:05:12,840 --> 00:05:18,320
Buyers re-entered the market at these 
lower prices, bidding prices back up.
  

57
00:05:18,320 --> 00:05:23,080
This back-and-forth between buyers and 
sellers continues throughout the period,  

58
00:05:23,080 --> 00:05:28,960
resulting in a relatively small real body (which 
is the difference between the open and close),  

59
00:05:28,960 --> 00:05:34,880
compared to the total range of the candle 
(the distance from the high to the low).
  

60
00:05:34,880 --> 00:05:39,840
From a psychological perspective, these 
candles indicate a market in a state of  

61
00:05:39,840 --> 00:05:44,640
high uncertainty and indecision.
Neither buyers nor sellers are  

62
00:05:44,640 --> 00:05:49,720
able to maintain control for long.
The long wicks on both sides suggest  

63
00:05:49,720 --> 00:05:56,560
that both bullish and bearish sentiment is 
present, but neither side has a clear advantage.
  

64
00:05:56,560 --> 00:06:01,280
This type of price action often occurs 
at key turning points in the market,  

65
00:06:01,280 --> 00:06:05,080
or after a prolonged trend.
It signifies that the previous  

66
00:06:05,080 --> 00:06:11,600
trend is losing momentum and that a shift 
in market sentiment may be underway.
  

67
00:06:11,600 --> 00:06:18,080
Candlesticks with long upper wicks and little 
to no lower wick can signal a potential shift  

68
00:06:18,080 --> 00:06:25,320
in market sentiment and supply/demand dynamics.
 
As the candle opens, buyers are in control. They  

69
00:06:25,320 --> 00:06:31,600
aggressively push prices higher, extending the 
uptrend or rally from the previous periods. 

70
00:06:31,600 --> 00:06:36,000
This buying pressure is reflected in 
the long upper wick, which shows the  

71
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:41,840
highest price reached during the period.
 
As prices reach these levels sellers begin  

72
00:06:41,840 --> 00:06:48,200
to emerge, stepping in to take advantage of 
what they perceive as overextended prices. 

73
00:06:48,200 --> 00:06:54,640
They start to outweigh the buyers, creating 
selling pressure that drives prices back down.
  

74
00:06:54,640 --> 00:06:59,080
From a supply and demand perspective, 
these candles indicate a potential  

75
00:06:59,080 --> 00:07:03,360
exhaustion point in an uptrend.
At the higher prices, supply begins  

76
00:07:03,360 --> 00:07:10,360
to outweigh demand as more participants view 
the price as overextended and look to sell. 
  

77
00:07:10,360 --> 00:07:16,400
This shift in the supply/demand balance is what 
causes the price to fall back from the highs. 

78
00:07:16,400 --> 00:07:21,720
Psychologically, these candles can signal 
a potential change in market sentiment. 
  

79
00:07:21,720 --> 00:07:28,400
The long upper wick suggests that the bullish 
momentum that drove prices higher is decreasing. 

80
00:07:28,400 --> 00:07:32,840
It's a visual representation of a 
"buying exhaustion" - the point at  

81
00:07:32,840 --> 00:07:40,040
which the upward trend loses steam as fewer 
buyers are willing to push prices higher.
 

82
00:07:40,040 --> 00:07:47,080
The candlestick with only a long lower wick can 
also signal a potential shift in market sentiment. 

83
00:07:47,080 --> 00:07:52,680
As the period begins, sellers are firmly 
in control. They aggressively push prices  

84
00:07:52,680 --> 00:07:57,920
lower, extending the downtrend or 
decline from the previous periods. 

85
00:07:57,920 --> 00:08:02,440
This selling pressure is reflected 
in the long lower wick, which shows  

86
00:08:02,440 --> 00:08:08,720
the lowest price reached during the timeframe.
 
However, buyers are sensing an opportunity in the  

87
00:08:08,720 --> 00:08:15,200
oversold conditions, and they start to step in.
They begin to outweigh the sellers, creating a  

88
00:08:15,200 --> 00:08:21,040
buying pressure that drives prices back up.
 
From a supply and demand perspective,  

89
00:08:21,040 --> 00:08:25,760
these candles indicate a potential 
exhaustion point in a downtrend. 

90
00:08:25,760 --> 00:08:29,440
At the lower prices, demand 
begins to outweigh supply  

91
00:08:30,080 --> 00:08:35,360
as more participants view the price 
as undervalued and looked to buy. 

92
00:08:35,360 --> 00:08:41,040
This shift in the supply/demand balance is what 
caused the price to rebound from the lows.
  

93
00:08:41,040 --> 00:08:46,600
Psychologically, these candles can signal 
a potential change in market sentiment. 

94
00:08:46,600 --> 00:08:51,600
It's a visual representation of a "selling 
climax" - the point at which the downward  

95
00:08:51,600 --> 00:08:57,880
trend loses steam as fewer sellers 
are willing to drive prices lower.
  

96
00:08:57,880 --> 00:09:04,000
Gap candles reflect dramatic shifts in 
overnight sentiment and supply/demand dynamics. 

97
00:09:04,000 --> 00:09:09,680
An up gap candle occurs when the lowest price 
of a candle is higher than the highest price  

98
00:09:09,680 --> 00:09:13,080
of the previous candle.
Visually, this leaves a  

99
00:09:13,080 --> 00:09:18,720
blank space or "gap" on the chart.
 
Psychologically, an up gap candle  

100
00:09:18,720 --> 00:09:25,120
suggests a significant shift in sentiment in 
favor of the buyers. It indicates that buying  

101
00:09:25,120 --> 00:09:31,360
pressure has intensified dramatically, to the 
point where sellers were unable to drive the  

102
00:09:31,360 --> 00:09:37,520
price down to the level of the previous close.
 
It could reflect a more gradual shift in market  

103
00:09:37,520 --> 00:09:44,360
psychology, where a critical mass of buyers has 
decided that the current price is undervalued. 

104
00:09:44,360 --> 00:09:49,680
Either way, the up gap signals that 
demand has suddenly outpaced supply,  

105
00:09:49,680 --> 00:09:54,920
and that the balance of power has shifted 
decisively in favor of the buyers. 
  

106
00:09:54,920 --> 00:10:00,880
This can serve as a powerful signal to look for 
buying opportunities, as the increased buying  

107
00:10:00,880 --> 00:10:08,040
pressure could lead to further upside momentum.
 
A down gap candle occurs when the highest price  

108
00:10:08,040 --> 00:10:12,920
of a candle is lower than the 
lowest price of the previous one. 

109
00:10:12,920 --> 00:10:18,960
Psychologically, this suggests a significant 
shift in sentiment in favor of the sellers. 

110
00:10:18,960 --> 00:10:24,840
Selling pressure has intensified dramatically, 
to the point where buyers were unable to drive  

111
00:10:24,840 --> 00:10:31,320
the price up to the level of the previous close.
 
It could reflect a more gradual shift in market  

112
00:10:31,320 --> 00:10:38,240
psychology, where a critical mass of sellers has 
decided that the current price is overvalued. 

113
00:10:38,240 --> 00:10:43,320
This increased selling pressure could 
lead to further downside momentum.
  

114
00:10:43,320 --> 00:10:49,060
Also, gap candles don't always lead to 
continued movement in the direction of the gap. 

115
00:10:49,060 --> 00:10:53,520
Sometimes, a gap candle can be a signal 
of exhaustion, where the move has  

116
00:10:53,520 --> 00:10:58,680
pushed the price to an unsustainable 
level, leading to a rapid reversal.
  

117
00:10:58,680 --> 00:11:04,200
This is why many traders pay close attention 
to gap fills - instances where the price moves  

118
00:11:04,200 --> 00:11:11,400
back to fill the blank space left by the gap. 
 
Now, very important: we're often tempted to react  

119
00:11:11,400 --> 00:11:16,720
immediately to a single dramatic candle.
For example, you're watching a market  

120
00:11:16,720 --> 00:11:21,680
that's been in a steady uptrend, and 
suddenly, a massive candle appears,  

121
00:11:21,680 --> 00:11:27,800
much bigger than the previous candles.
It's a bearish, compelling pattern, no doubt!
  

122
00:11:27,800 --> 00:11:33,680
But here's the thing: the market is a 
complex, noisy place. At any given moment,  

123
00:11:33,680 --> 00:11:40,080
there are many factors influencing price action.
A single candle, no matter how dramatic,  

124
00:11:40,080 --> 00:11:46,240
is just a snapshot of a very brief period 
of time. It doesn't tell the whole story.
  

125
00:11:46,240 --> 00:11:50,480
That single dramatic candle it's 
worth noting, but it's not enough  

126
00:11:50,480 --> 00:11:55,920
on its own to base a conviction on.
You need to gather more evidence.
 
 
  

127
00:11:55,920 --> 00:12:01,440
This is a critical lesson for all traders to 
learn, but especially for beginners. The market  

128
00:12:01,440 --> 00:12:08,200
has a way of generating all sorts of dramatic, 
compelling signals on a minute-by-minute basis.  

129
00:12:08,200 --> 00:12:13,760
It's easy to get caught up in the excitement, 
to feel like you need to react to every candle.
  

130
00:12:13,760 --> 00:12:18,720
But the successful traders, the ones 
who last in this game, know better. 

131
00:12:18,720 --> 00:12:24,360
They know that the real edge comes not from 
reacting to every signal, but from patiently  

132
00:12:24,360 --> 00:12:28,800
waiting for the high-quality setups. 
 
That’s why in the future videos,  

133
00:12:28,800 --> 00:12:34,680
I plan to talk about the psychology of support 
and resistance levels, and how to combine them  

134
00:12:34,680 --> 00:12:50,320
with candlestick analysis. And in the meantime, go 
ahead and watch one of these price action videos.

